columns.name: Site ID
columns.description: The unique ID for each LinkNYC kiosk site in the format: Borough-Community Board-Payphone ID (e.g., mn-03-123265)

columns.name: Planned Kiosk Type
columns.description: Indicates style of kiosk (LINK1.0, LINK5G, and LINK5G_NoAd) or public payphone.

columns.name: Installation Status
columns.description: Indicates the current status, including planning for utility connections, DOT permitting, and construction.

columns.name: PPT ID
columns.description: An 6-digit ID generated by the database - a unique number for each LINK and Pay Public Telephone (PPT).

columns.name: Legacy ID
columns.description: The ID number for the LinkNYC kiosk.

columns.name: Borough
columns.description: The borough where the approved kiosk will be located.

columns.name: Council District
columns.description: Council District is the lawmaking body of the City of New York.  There are 51 districts throughout NYC's five boroughs.

columns.name: Community Board
columns.description: Community Board: An appointed advisory group from a variety of districts throughout NYC's five boroughs.  They deal with issues such as zoning, land usage, and any other matter related to the quality of life of their residents.

columns.name: Street Address
columns.description: The address of the building adjacent to the approved kiosk location.

columns.name: Cross Street 1
columns.description: One of the closest streets to the approved kiosk location.

columns.name: Cross Street 2
columns.description: One of the closest streets to the approved kiosk location.

columns.name: IxN Corner
columns.description: The direction the Kiosk is facing.

columns.name: Postcode
columns.description: Five (5) digit postal code assigned by the United States Postal Service.

columns.name: Zoning
columns.description: The type of zoning a kiosk is located in, displayed by its first letter followed by its zone.

columns.name: Latitude
columns.description: Points that fall North or South of the Equator, expressed in degrees.

columns.name: Longitude
columns.description: Points that fall East or West of the Prime Meridian, expressed in degrees.

columns.name: Installation Complete
columns.description: Date when LINK kiosk/public pay phone was installed.

columns.name: Activation Complete
columns.description: Date when LINK kiosk/public pay phone was activated.

columns.name: Neighborhood Tabulation Area (NTA)
columns.description: Neighborhood Tabulation Areas (NTAs) are aggregates of census tracts that were created to project populations at a small area level, from 2000 to 2030, for PlaNYC, the long-term sustainability plan for New York City.

columns.name: Building Identification Number (BIN)
columns.description: Building Identification Number (BIN) - Every real estate property has an assigned 7-digit number issued by the Department of City Planning.

columns.name: Borough-Block-Lot (BBL)
columns.description: Borough Block Lot (BBL) - Every real estate property is identified by a set of 3 numbers for taxes, zoning, construction, and other purposes.

columns.name: Census Tract (CT)
columns.description: Census Tract (CT) - Permanent statistical subdivisions to provide a stable set of geographic units for the presentation of statistical data.

columns.name: Location
columns.description: The exact latitude and longitude of each Kiosk.

fields.name: Agency

view.description: LinkNYC is the City’s program to provide free high-speed Wi-Fi, nationwide calling, a dedicated 911 button, charging ports for mobile devices, and access to social services. The City has recently begun to roll out a new and improved design of the original LinkNYC kiosk: Link5G. This new design will provide all of the amenities of LinkNYC kiosks, with the added benefit of 4G and 5G connectivity to enhance mobile telecommunications networks. This dataset lists locations for LinkNYC kiosks plus four public payphones in the five boroughs.

relatedViews.name: LinkNYC Map
relatedViews.description:
This map shows locations where a LinkNYC kiosk has been approved and installed.
It includes sites that have replaced public pay telephones (PPT) and new sites that have been reviewed by community and elected officials.
